very split between
Mondale and Gary Hart.

10:27.594 --> 10:31.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So it had a similar feeling to
this.

10:31.664 --> 10:38.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, nonetheless, in the
nomination of the
first woman as vice president of
a major party,

10:38.438 --> 10:40.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it was thunderous.

10:40.306 --> 10:43.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's what will happen with
Hillary Clinton,
even beyond, because she's going
to be nominated

10:43.610 --> 10:47.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for president, the most powerful
person in
the world.

10:47.680 --> 10:49.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's very exciting.

10:49.048 --> 10:51.718 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it will be
historic, as
we have been saying.

10:51.751 --> 10:57.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But should it be a factor in how
people vote,
the fact that she would be the
first woman

10:57.390 --> 10:58.825 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
president, the fact that she is
a woman?

10:58.858 --> 11:00.593 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

11:00.627 --> 11:02.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NANCY PELOSI: I don't think -- I
think that
people want to know what the
election of a

11:02.428 --> 11:05.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
particular person means in their
lives.

11:05.365 --> 11:07.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is your vision?

11:07.200 --> 11:10.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What is your plan to get
something done that
affects me?

11:10.837 --> 11:15.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have always said, in my
own rise in
the leadership, please don't
ever ask anybody

11:15.575 --> 11:17.844 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to vote for me because I'm a
woman.

11:17.877 --> 11:22.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That happens to be, in my view,
an enhancement,
but, nonetheless, it's all about
who is the

11:22.215 --> 11:23.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
best person for the job.

11:24.017 --> 11:26.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hillary Clinton is the best
person for the
job.

11:26.452 --> 11:30.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She will go into the Oval Office
before prepared
even than President Obama.

11:30.490 --> 11:31.891 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He has said that himself.

11:31.925 --> 11:34.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Better prepared than President
Bush, George
W. Bush.

11:34.260 --> 11:35.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Better prepared than her own
husband.

11:35.995 --> 11:41.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, she has a vision, she has
knowledge
and judgment.

11:41.100 --> 11:45.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She is a strategic thinker,
based on her experience
and her connection.

11:45.071 --> 11:50.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know something about power,
being the first
woman speaker of the House.

11:50.209 --> 11:56.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Actually, the legislative branch
is the first
article of the Constitution, and
so president,

11:56.416 --> 11:59.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
vice president, speaker of the
House, third
highest.

11:59.118 --> 12:07.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, for me, it's particularly
almost emotional
to think that she will have that
much power

12:07.760 --> 12:12.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to help develop a consensus in
our country
and be the leader of the free
world.

12:12.865 --> 12:15.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Power is the word.

12:15.735 --> 12:18.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nancy Pelosi, minority leader of
the House
of Representatives, thank you so
much for

12:18.738 --> 12:19.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
joining us.

12:19.739 --> 12:20.707 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

12:20.740 --> 12:21.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NANCY PELOSI: My pleasure.

12:21.741 --> 12:23.610 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

12:23.643 --> 12:23.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Who has already
made history
herself by being the first woman
in that position.

12:24.010 --> 12:24.711 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

12:24.744 --> 12:26.379 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

12:26.412 --> 12:27.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NANCY PELOSI: But I'm happy to
relinquish
the title of the highest elected
woman in

12:27.380 --> 12:28.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the history of our country.

12:28.781 --> 12:30.550 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

12:30.583 --> 12:34.587 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we turn to
the second part
of our series exploring Hillary
Clinton's

12:34.621 --> 12:38.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
life -- tonight, the eight years
she spent
in the White House.

12:38.391 --> 12:43.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her tenure as first lady can be
categorized
as atypical, and even
controversial at times.

12:43.563 --> 12:48.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She logged many firsts, first
presidential
spouse with a graduate degree,
first to testify

12:48.968 --> 12:56.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
before a grand jury, and the
first to have
an office in the West Wing of
the White House.

12:56.075 --> 13:01.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before the Clintons ever stepped
foot into
the White House in 1993, and she
was given

13:01.581 --> 13:06.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her own West Wing office, there
were hints
Hillary Clinton would be a
different kind

13:06.586 --> 13:08.521 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of first lady.

13:08.554 --> 13:10.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
I suppose I could have stayed
home and baked

13:10.056 --> 13:13.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cookies and had teas, but what I
decided to
do was to fulfill my profession.

13:13.259 --> 13:19.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That candid
comment early in
the '92 campaign didn't go over
well with

13:19.098 --> 13:23.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
voters, so she shifted to a more
traditional
role until Election Day.

13:23.670 --> 13:28.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But as soon as her husband was
elected, she
was again a public player.

13:28.107 --> 13:29.208 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: Hello.

13:29.242 --> 13:31.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is Hillary Clinton.

13:31.044 --> 13:34.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to thank you for letting
me speak with
you about an issue that is
central to our

13:34.747 --> 13:36.482 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
children's future.

13:36.516 --> 13:41.354 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Early on,
President Clinton
tapped his wife to steer a major
initiative,

13:41.387 --> 13:45.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
running the Task Force on
National Health
Care Reform.

13:45.324 --> 13:47.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Gergen was an aide to the
president
at the time.

13:47.860 --> 13:50.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID GERGEN, Former White House
Aide: She's
an extraordinarily competent
woman.

13:50.096 --> 13:53.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is very much on -- she knows
the issues
better than anybody I know,
including her

13:53.866 --> 13:54.967 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
husband.

13:55.001 --> 13:59.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was threatening to some
people, to some
voters.

13:59.372 --> 14:05.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Men would -- of the older
generation would
say, I would be really proud if
my daughter

14:05.311 --> 14:11.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
grew up to be like Hillary
Clinton, to be
the kind of pathbreaker she is,
but I sure

14:11.784 --> 14:13.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as hell am glad that my wife
isn't.

14:13.352 --> 14:16.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: Thank
you very much,
Mr. Chairman.

14:16.089 --> 14:20.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the beginning,
the health
care effort looked promising,
says author

14:20.626 --> 14:22.328 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Rebecca Traister.

14:22.361 --> 14:24.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REBECCA TRAISTER, Author, "All
The Single
Ladies: Unmarried Women and the
Rise of an

14:24.230 --> 14:26.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Independent Nation": When she
first took on
the project, and initially
testified in front

14:26.666 --> 14:32.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Congress about health care
reform, it actually
looked like it might go well.

14:32.705 --> 14:35.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was already a very divisive
figure.

14:35.308 --> 14:36.275 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
People hated her.

14:36.309 --> 14:37.276 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
People loved her.

14:37.310 --> 14:39.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was so clearly smart,
competent.

14:39.378 --> 14:41.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Her approval ratings went way
up.

14:41.047 --> 14:42.849 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
People liked it.

14:42.882 --> 14:46.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But as weeks
passed, Clinton's
health care plan was attacked by
the right

14:46.185 --> 14:47.687 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and the left.

14:47.720 --> 14:50.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Conservatives called it a
government takeover.

14:50.757 --> 14:56.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even with a Democratic majority
in Congress,
the bill never made it out of
committee.

14:56.329 --> 15:01.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hillary had recruited dozens of
experts to
help craft an elaborate plan for
universal

15:01.901 --> 15:07.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
coverage, but she had insisted
most of the
work be done in secret.

15:07.140 --> 15:12.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David Gergen says it was that
and the lack
of political outreach that led
to failure.

15:12.245 --> 15:15.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID GERGEN: She hadn't learned
yet to play
the Washington game.

15:15.982 --> 15:20.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The collapse of
the health
care initiative was one of the
major factors

15:20.119 --> 15:24.290 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in the GOP's takeover of
Congress the following
year.

15:24.323 --> 15:30.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During Bill Clinton's second
term, Hillary
was successful in her push for a
program that

15:30.396 --> 15:36.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enabled Washington to partner
with states
to ensure health coverage for
uninsured children.

15:36.903 --> 15:42.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, unlike the first four
years, she spent
less time in the West Wing, and
more time

15:42.708 --> 15:45.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
traveling abroad, much of it
promoting women's
rights.

15:45.978 --> 15:51.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: It is no
longer acceptable
to discuss women's rights as
separate from

15:51.818 --> 15:53.519 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
human rights.

15:53.553 --> 15:57.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Traister
describes it as a
retreat into a more traditional
first lady

15:57.790 --> 15:59.325 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
role.

15:59.358 --> 16:01.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REBECCA TRAISTER: She and
Chelsea did a lot
of traveling around the world.

16:01.394 --> 16:05.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She wrote a book called, "Dear
Socks, Dear
Buddy," notes to the White House
pets.

16:05.998 --> 16:12.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
She was blamed so
enthusiastically for what
happened with health care
reform, and she

16:12.071 --> 16:21.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
was really attacked so
forcefully, that it
precipitated a real retreat by
Hillary from

16:21.781 --> 16:25.318 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this divisive public role that
she had held
within the administration.

16:25.351 --> 16:29.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Hillary was also
at the center
of a string of controversies.

16:29.822 --> 16:35.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Clintons' involvement in a
failed Arkansas
land deal known as Whitewater
would follow

16:35.361 --> 16:37.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
both of them through his
presidency.

16:37.396 --> 16:43.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID GERGEN: I think one of the
most troubling
moments for me at the White
House came over

16:43.836 --> 16:44.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Whitewater issue.

16:44.971 --> 16:47.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Former White
House aide David
Gergen:

16:47.573 --> 16:52.879 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID GERGEN: I had a
conversation with the
president, and we got his assent
to give over

16:52.912 --> 16:54.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the documents to The Washington
Post.

16:54.447 --> 16:58.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But then the president said:
"Before we do
this, you got to remember this.

16:58.951 --> 17:00.286 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Both Hillary and I were involved
in this.

17:00.319 --> 17:03.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We can't release the documents
without her
blessing as well.

17:03.756 --> 17:06.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, by the way, David, you
ought to go get
it."

17:06.626 --> 17:12.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I made the effort to see her,
and try to persuade
her to give over the documents,
and I was

17:12.498 --> 17:15.034 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ultimately very, very
unsuccessful.

17:15.067 --> 17:20.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: For years,
Hillary Clinton
resisted calls to release
documents related

17:20.740 --> 17:22.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to Whitewater and other
controversies.

17:22.875 --> 17:28.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That, in turn, drew more
attention from the
news media and ultimately led to
the appointment

17:28.848 --> 17:30.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of a special prosecutor.

17:30.783 --> 17:34.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID GERGEN: If you stick to
secrecy too
much in the White House -- and
there's a temptation

17:34.487 --> 17:38.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for every White House to do that
-- but if
you stick too closely to
temptation, you can

17:38.758 --> 17:40.293 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
pay a big, big price.

17:40.326 --> 17:42.161 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And she paid a price for it.

17:42.194 --> 17:45.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: The
conventional wisdom
about Whitewater always is, take
any straw

17:45.798 --> 17:47.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you can to go on.

17:47.466 --> 17:50.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I don't have any doubt that
there are
those who will say this should
go on.

17:50.169 --> 17:52.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I just would like to tell them,
go on where?

17:52.738 --> 17:54.607 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have been going on for four
years.

17:54.640 --> 17:59.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
